  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — `apps/crawler`\n\n**Current state: zero tests.** No `tests/` directory, no `conftest.py`, nothing collected by pytest — despite `pytest>=9.1.1` already declared as a dev dependency in `pyproject.toml`. This is a from-scratch coverage plan for `base.py`, `providers.py`, `main.py`, `models.py`.\n\nOne structural note unrelated to tests but worth flagging: `data/`, `state/`, and `logs/` all have a `radiomadagasikara-rnm` entry, but no `RadioMadagasikaraRNM` class exists in `providers.py`'s `PROVIDERS` dict — either a removed provider or a registration that got dropped.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `base.py` — pure/unit-testable functions\n\n#### `parse_french_date` (base.py:90)\nUntested. Handles two formats + French month name variants (with/without accents), and returns `None` on failure.\n\n**Gaps:** accented vs non-accented months (`fevrier` vs `février`), single vs double-digit day, invalid month name, empty string, no match at all, ambiguous text with extra surrounding words.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom base import parse_french_date\n\nclass TestParseFrenchDate:\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"text,expected\", [\n        (\"22 juin 2019\", \"2019-06-22\"),\n        (\"octobre 30, 2017\", \"2017-10-30\"),\n        (\"1 février 2020\", \"2020-02-01\"),\n        (\"1 fevrier 2020\", \"2020-02-01\"),  # unaccented variant\n        (\"Publié le 5 mars 2021 à 14h\", \"2021-03-05\"),  # embedded in surrounding text\n    ])\n    def test_valid_formats(self, text, expected):\n        assert parse_french_date(text) == expected\n\n    def test_unknown_month_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_french_date(\"22 blorpuary 2019\") is None\n\n    def test_no_date_in_text_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_french_date(\"no date here\") is None\n\n    def test_empty_string_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_french_date(\"\") is None\n```\n\n#### `parse_numeric_date` (base.py:107)\nUntested. Regex-based `DD/MM/YYYY`, tolerant of trailing time.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom base import parse_numeric_date\n\nclass TestParseNumericDate:\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"text,expected\", [\n        (\"22/06/2019\", \"2019-06-22\"),\n        (\"22/06/2019 14:30\", \"2019-06-22\"),\n        (\"Publié le 05/03/2021\", \"2021-03-05\"),\n    ])\n    def test_valid(self, text, expected):\n        assert parse_numeric_date(text) == expected\n\n    def test_no_match_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_numeric_date(\"not a date\") is None\n\n    def test_invalid_calendar_date_raises(self):\n        # day=32 passes the regex but datetime() will raise ValueError —\n        # currently uncaught. This is a real gap: confirm intended behavior.\n        with pytest.raises(ValueError):\n            parse_numeric_date(\"32/13/2019\")\n```\nNote: the last case is a genuine **missing error-handling gap** — malformed-but-regex-matching dates (`32/13/2019`) will raise unhandled inside `parse_article`, and since `crawl()` only catches exceptions around `parse_article` as a whole (base.py:291-295), it's silently swallowed as a per-article failure rather than surfaced. Worth deciding if that's acceptable or if `parse_numeric_date`/`parse_french_date` should validate and return `None` instead.\n\n#### `_fetch_xml` (base.py:48)\nUntested. Two non-obvious behaviors called out in comments: gzip-sniffing regardless of headers, and stripping a leading newline before XML parsing.\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\nfrom base import _fetch_xml\nimport gzip\n\nclass TestFetchXml:\n    @patch(\"base.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_plain_xml(self, mock_urlopen):\n        mock_urlopen.return_value.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b\"<urlset></urlset>\"\n        assert _fetch_xml(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\") == \"<urlset></urlset>\"\n\n    @patch(\"base.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_gzip_sniffed_regardless_of_headers(self, mock_urlopen):\n        compressed = gzip.compress(b\"<urlset></urlset>\")\n        mock_urlopen.return_value.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = compressed\n        assert _fetch_xml(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\") == \"<urlset></urlset>\"\n\n    @patch(\"base.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_strips_leading_whitespace(self, mock_urlopen):\n        mock_urlopen.return_value.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b\"\\n<urlset></urlset>\"\n        result = _fetch_xml(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\")\n        assert result.startswith(\"<urlset\")\n\n    @patch(\"base.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_undecodable_bytes_replaced_not_raised(self, mock_urlopen):\n        mock_urlopen.return_value.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b\"<urlset>\\xff\\xfe</urlset>\"\n        result = _fetch_xml(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\")\n        assert \"\\ufffd\" in result  # errors=\"replace\"\n```\n**Missing error-handling test:** no coverage of network failure (`urllib.error.URLError`, timeout) propagating out of `_fetch_xml` — confirm callers (`discover_sitemap_urls`) handle it, or don't (it currently propagates all the way to `crawl()`'s outer `except Exception` at base.py:328, which is itself untested — see §3).\n\n#### `discover_sitemap_urls` (base.py:61)\nUntested. Recursive sitemap-index walking, namespace-stripped `loc` extraction, and the specific edge case called out in the comment: nested `<image:loc>` must NOT be picked up.\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom base import discover_sitemap_urls\n\nclass TestDiscoverSitemapUrls:\n    @patch(\"base._fetch_xml\")\n    def test_flat_urlset(self, mock_fetch):\n        mock_fetch.return_value = \"\"\"<urlset xmlns=\"http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9\">\n            <url><loc>http://example.com/a</loc></url>\n            <url><loc>http://example.com/b</loc></url>\n        </urlset>\"\"\"\n        assert list(discover_sitemap_urls(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\")) == [\n            \"http://example.com/a\", \"http://example.com/b\"\n        ]\n\n    @patch(\"base._fetch_xml\")\n    def test_sitemap_index_recurses(self, mock_fetch):\n        index_xml = \"\"\"<sitemapindex xmlns=\"http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9\">\n            <sitemap><loc>http://example.com/sub1.xml</loc></sitemap>\n        </sitemapindex>\"\"\"\n        leaf_xml = \"\"\"<urlset><url><loc>http://example.com/article-1</loc></url></urlset>\"\"\"\n        mock_fetch.side_effect = [index_xml, leaf_xml]\n        assert list(discover_sitemap_urls(\"http://example.com/index.xml\")) == [\n            \"http://example.com/article-1\"\n        ]\n\n    @patch(\"base._fetch_xml\")\n    def test_ignores_nested_image_loc(self, mock_fetch):\n        # image:loc localname-matches \"loc\" one level deeper — must not be yielded\n        mock_fetch.return_value = \"\"\"<urlset xmlns:image=\"http://example.com/image\">\n            <url>\n                <loc>http://example.com/article-1</loc>\n                <image:image><image:loc>http://example.com/photo.jpg</image:loc></image:image>\n            </url>\n        </urlset>\"\"\"\n        assert list(discover_sitemap_urls(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\")) == [\n            \"http://example.com/article-1\"\n        ]\n\n    @patch(\"base._fetch_xml\")\n    def test_is_lazy_stops_after_enough_pulled(self, mock_fetch):\n        # generator: caller stops pulling once satisfied — sub-sitemaps beyond that\n        # should never be fetched. Verify _fetch_xml call count.\n        index_xml = \"\"\"<sitemapindex>\n            <sitemap><loc>http://example.com/sub1.xml</loc></sitemap>\n            <sitemap><loc>http://example.com/sub2.xml</loc></sitemap>\n        </sitemapindex>\"\"\"\n        leaf_xml = \"\"\"<urlset><url><loc>http://example.com/a1</loc></url></urlset>\"\"\"\n        mock_fetch.side_effect = [index_xml, leaf_xml]\n        gen = discover_sitemap_urls(\"http://example.com/index.xml\")\n        next(gen)  # only pull one\n        assert mock_fetch.call_count == 2  # index + sub1 only, sub2 never fetched\n\n    @patch(\"base._fetch_xml\")\n    def test_malformed_xml_raises(self, mock_fetch):\n        mock_fetch.return_value = \"<not><valid\"\n        with pytest.raises(ET.ParseError):\n            list(discover_sitemap_urls(\"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\"))\n```\nThe laziness test directly exercises the behavior the docstring claims (\"we only fetch as many sitemap sub-files as actually needed\") — currently unverified by anything.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `base.py` — `NewsSource` (state/persistence + parsing pipeline)\n\nThese need a minimal concrete subclass fixture since `NewsSource` is abstract-by-convention (no `@abstractmethod`, but `parse_article`/`crawl` assume `selectors`/`source_name` are set).\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Article, SiteSelectors\nfrom base import NewsSource\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef source_cls(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    import base\n    monkeypatch.setattr(base, \"STATE_DIR\", tmp_path / \"state\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(base, \"LOG_DIR\", tmp_path / \"logs\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(base, \"DATA_DIR\", tmp_path / \"data\")\n\n    class FakeSource(NewsSource):\n        source_name = \"fake-provider\"\n        selectors = SiteSelectors(title=\"h1\", body=\"p\")\n        sitemap_url = \"http://example.com/sitemap.xml\"\n\n    return FakeSource\n```\n\n#### `_load_state` / `_save_state` (base.py:138-149)\nUntested. Default when no file exists, atomic-write behavior (tmp file replace), round-trip.\n\n```python\nclass TestState:\n    def test_load_state_defaults_when_missing(self, source_cls):\n        state = source_cls()._load_state()\n        assert state == {\"seen_urls\": [], \"total_saved\": 0}\n\n    def test_save_then_load_roundtrip(self, source_cls):\n        src = source_cls()\n        src._save_state({\"seen_urls\": [\"http://a\"], \"total_saved\": 1})\n        assert src._load_state() == {\"seen_urls\": [\"http://a\"], \"total_saved\": 1}\n\n    def test_save_state_no_leftover_tmp_file(self, source_cls, tmp_path):\n        src = source_cls()\n        src._save_state({\"seen_urls\": [], \"total_saved\": 0})\n        assert not src._state_path.with_suffix(\".json.tmp\").exists()\n\n    def test_unicode_preserved(self, source_cls):\n        src = source_cls()\n        src._save_state({\"seen_urls\": [\"été\"], \"total_saved\": 0})\n        assert src._load_state()[\"seen_urls\"] == [\"été\"]\n```\n**Missing error-handling test:** corrupt/truncated JSON state file (crash mid-write despite the \"atomic write\" comment claiming this can't happen post-write — but a file corrupted by an external process, or a genuinely interrupted `.tmp.replace()`, isn't covered). `_load_state` will raise `json.JSONDecodeError` uncaught — confirm that's intended (crash loudly) vs. should recover.\n\n#### `fetch` (base.py:162)\nUntested dispatch logic — `needs_stealth` flag routing to `StealthyFetcher` vs `Fetcher`.\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\n\nclass TestFetch:\n    @patch(\"base.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_uses_plain_fetcher_by_default(self, mock_get, source_cls):\n        source_cls().fetch(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        mock_get.assert_called_once()\n\n    @patch(\"base.StealthyFetcher.fetch\")\n    def test_uses_stealthy_fetcher_when_flagged(self, mock_stealth, source_cls):\n        source_cls.needs_stealth = True\n        source_cls().fetch(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        mock_stealth.assert_called_once_with(\"http://example.com/a\")\n```\n\n#### `list_article_urls` (base.py:167)\nUntested — the `NotImplementedError` branch when `sitemap_url` is unset is a real gap (this is exactly the contract that `MadagascarTribune`/`FreeNews`/`Moov` rely on by overriding it).\n\n```python\nclass TestListArticleUrls:\n    def test_raises_when_no_sitemap_and_not_overridden(self, source_cls):\n        source_cls.sitemap_url = None\n        with pytest.raises(NotImplementedError, match=\"no sitemap_url set\"):\n            list(source_cls().list_article_urls())\n\n    @patch(\"base.discover_sitemap_urls\")\n    def test_delegates_to_discover_sitemap_urls(self, mock_discover, source_cls):\n        mock_discover.return_value = iter([\"http://example.com/a\"])\n        assert list(source_cls().list_article_urls()) == [\"http://example.com/a\"]\n```\n\n#### `parse_article` (base.py:174) — the core parsing logic, entirely untested\nThis is the highest-value gap: title/body/author/date/category/cover_image/embed_url extraction, with several conditional branches (`published_date_attr` vs text parsing, `french`/`numeric`/raw date formats, iframe vs `<video>` fallback, missing-title short-circuit).\n\nNeeds a fake \"page\" object matching the scrapling `.css()`/`.attrib`/`.get_all_text()` interface — worth building a small test double once and reusing.\n\n```python\nclass FakeElement:\n    def __init__(self, text=\"\", attrib=None):\n        self._text = text\n        self.attrib = attrib or {}\n    def get_all_text(self, strip=True):\n        return self._text.strip() if strip else self._text\n\nclass FakeQuery(list):\n    @property\n    def first(self):\n        return self[0] if self else None\n\nclass FakePage:\n    def __init__(self, elements: dict):\n        self._elements = elements  # selector -> list[FakeElement]\n    def css(self, selector):\n        return FakeQuery(self._elements.get(selector, []))\n\nclass TestParseArticle:\n    def _source(self, source_cls, page):\n        src = source_cls()\n        src.fetch = lambda url: page\n        return src\n\n    def test_missing_title_returns_none(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({})  # no title element\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article is None\n\n    def test_full_article_parsed(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\n            \"h1\": [FakeElement(\"My Title\")],\n            \"p\": [FakeElement(\"Para one.\"), FakeElement(\"Para two.\")],\n            \"meta[property='og:image']\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"content\": \"http://img/cover.jpg\"})],\n        })\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.title == \"My Title\"\n        assert article.body == \"Para one.\\n\\nPara two.\"\n        assert article.cover_image == \"http://img/cover.jpg\"\n\n    def test_empty_paragraphs_excluded_from_body(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")], \"p\": [FakeElement(\"  \"), FakeElement(\"Real text\")]})\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.body == \"Real text\"\n\n    def test_published_date_from_attr(self, source_cls):\n        source_cls.selectors = SiteSelectors(\n            title=\"h1\", body=\"p\", published_date=\"time\", published_date_attr=\"datetime\"\n        )\n        page = FakePage({\n            \"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")],\n            \"time\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"datetime\": \"2020-01-01\"})],\n        })\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.published_date == \"2020-01-01\"\n\n    def test_published_date_french_format(self, source_cls):\n        source_cls.selectors = SiteSelectors(\n            title=\"h1\", body=\"p\", published_date=\".date\", published_date_format=\"french\"\n        )\n        page = FakePage({\"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")], \".date\": [FakeElement(\"22 juin 2019\")]})\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.published_date == \"2019-06-22\"\n\n    def test_embed_url_prefers_iframe_over_video(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\n            \"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")],\n            \"iframe\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"http://embed/video\"})],\n            \"video source\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"http://embed/fallback.mp4\"})],\n        })\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.embed_url == \"http://embed/video\"\n\n    def test_embed_url_skips_about_blank_iframe(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\n            \"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")],\n            \"iframe\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"about:blank\"})],\n            \"video source\": [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"http://embed/fallback.mp4\"})],\n        })\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.embed_url == \"http://embed/fallback.mp4\"\n\n    def test_no_author_selector_yields_none(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")]})\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.author is None\n\n    def test_author_selector_present_but_element_missing(self, source_cls):\n        source_cls.selectors = SiteSelectors(title=\"h1\", body=\"p\", author=\".byline\")\n        page = FakePage({\"h1\": [FakeElement(\"T\")]})  # .byline not in page\n        article = self._source(source_cls, page).parse_article(\"http://example.com/a\")\n        assert article.author is None\n```\n\n#### `_extract_images` (base.py:254)\nUntested — dedup, `data-src` preference over `src`, `data:` URI exclusion, relative→absolute resolution, cover-image-first ordering.\n\n```python\nclass TestExtractImages:\n    def test_cover_image_first(self, source_cls):\n        page = FakePage({\"article img, .entry-content img, .td-post-content img, .post-content img, .vcex-post-content img, figure img\": [\n            FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"http://example.com/body.jpg\"})\n        ]})\n        images = source_cls()._extract_images(page, \"http://example.com/a\", \"http://example.com/cover.jpg\")\n        assert images[0] == \"http://example.com/cover.jpg\"\n\n    def test_data_src_preferred_over_src(self, source_cls):\n        selector = source_cls._IMG_CONTAINERS\n        page = FakePage({selector: [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"placeholder.gif\", \"data-src\": \"real.jpg\"})]})\n        images = source_cls()._extract_images(page, \"http://example.com/a\", None)\n        assert images == [\"http://example.com/real.jpg\"]\n\n    def test_data_uri_excluded(self, source_cls):\n        selector = source_cls._IMG_CONTAINERS\n        page = FakePage({selector: [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"data:image/png;base64,AAAA\"})]})\n        images = source_cls()._extract_images(page, \"http://example.com/a\", None)\n        assert images == []\n\n    def test_dedup_across_cover_and_body(self, source_cls):\n        selector = source_cls._IMG_CONTAINERS\n        page = FakePage({selector: [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"http://example.com/dup.jpg\"})]})\n        images = source_cls()._extract_images(page, \"http://example.com/a\", \"http://example.com/dup.jpg\")\n        assert images == [\"http://example.com/dup.jpg\"]\n\n    def test_relative_url_resolved_against_article_url(self, source_cls):\n        selector = source_cls._IMG_CONTAINERS\n        page = FakePage({selector: [FakeElement(attrib={\"src\": \"/img/a.jpg\"})]})\n        images = source_cls()._extract_images(page, \"http://example.com/articles/a\", None)\n        assert images == [\"http://example.com/img/a.jpg\"]\n```\n\n#### `crawl` (base.py:273) — highest-risk orchestration logic, entirely untested\nThis is where resumability, error isolation, and stop-reason bookkeeping live. Given the amount of branching, it deserves its own dedicated test class with a fake `list_article_urls`/`parse_article`.\n\n**Gaps identified:**\n- already-seen URLs skipped without re-fetching\n- per-article exception → logged, skipped, loop continues (not marked seen → retried next run)\n- `parse_article` returning `None` → marked seen (never retried) — distinct from the exception case above\n- `limit <= 0` → unlimited, runs to exhaustion\n- `limit` reached mid-loop → returns early with correct `saved` list and `last_stopped_reason`\n- discovery-phase exception (`list_article_urls()` itself raising) → state saved with error reason, exception re-raised\n- `on_save` callback invoked once per saved article, not called for skips\n- state file's `total_saved` accumulates across calls (not reset per run)\n\n```python\nclass TestCrawl:\n    def _source_with(self, source_cls, urls, parse_results, monkeypatch):\n        src = source_cls()\n        monkeypatch.setattr(src, \"list_article_urls\", lambda: iter(urls))\n        def fake_parse(url):\n            result = parse_results[url]\n            if isinstance(result, Exception):\n                raise result\n            return result\n\n        monkeypatch.setattr(src, \"parse_article\", fake_parse)\n        return src\n\n    def _article(self, url):\n        return Article(url=url, title=\"T\", body=\"B\", author=None, published_date=None,\n                        category=None, source=\"fake-provider\", scraped_at=\"2020-01-01T00:00:00\")\n\n    def test_skips_already_seen_urls(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        src = source_cls()\n        src._save_state({\"seen_urls\": [\"http://a\"], \"total_saved\": 1})\n        monkeypatch.setattr(src, \"list_article_urls\", lambda: iter([\"http://a\", \"http://b\"]))\n        monkeypatch.setattr(src, \"parse_article\", lambda url: self._article(url))\n        saved = src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert [a.url for a in saved] == [\"http://b\"]\n\n    def test_parse_exception_skips_and_does_not_mark_seen(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, [\"http://a\"], {\"http://a\": RuntimeError(\"boom\")}, monkeypatch)\n        saved = src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert saved == []\n        assert src._load_state()[\"seen_urls\"] == []  # retried next run\n\n    def test_none_article_marks_seen_but_not_saved(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, [\"http://a\"], {\"http://a\": None}, monkeypatch)\n        saved = src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert saved == []\n        assert src._load_state()[\"seen_urls\"] == [\"http://a\"]  # never retried\n\n    def test_limit_zero_is_unlimited(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        urls = [f\"http://a{i}\" for i in range(5)]\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, urls, {u: self._article(u) for u in urls}, monkeypatch)\n        saved = src.crawl(limit=0)\n        assert len(saved) == 5\n\n    def test_stops_exactly_at_limit(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        urls = [f\"http://a{i}\" for i in range(5)]\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, urls, {u: self._article(u) for u in urls}, monkeypatch)\n        saved = src.crawl(limit=2)\n        assert len(saved) == 2\n        assert src._load_state()[\"last_stopped_reason\"] == \"limit reached\"\n\n    def test_exhausted_reason_when_fewer_than_limit(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        urls = [\"http://a\"]\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, urls, {\"http://a\": self._article(\"http://a\")}, monkeypatch)\n        src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert src._load_state()[\"last_stopped_reason\"] == \"exhausted\"\n\n    def test_discovery_failure_reraises_and_saves_reason(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        src = source_cls()\n        def failing_urls():\n            raise ConnectionError(\"network down\")\n            yield  # pragma: no cover\n        monkeypatch.setattr(src, \"list_article_urls\", failing_urls)\n        with pytest.raises(ConnectionError):\n            src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert \"error\" in src._load_state()[\"last_stopped_reason\"]\n\n    def test_on_save_called_once_per_saved_article(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        calls = []\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, [\"http://a\"], {\"http://a\": self._article(\"http://a\")}, monkeypatch)\n        src.crawl(limit=10, on_save=calls.append)\n        assert len(calls) == 1\n\n    def test_total_saved_accumulates_across_runs(self, source_cls, monkeypatch):\n        src = self._source_with(source_cls, [\"http://a\"], {\"http://a\": self._article(\"http://a\")}, monkeypatch)\n        src.crawl(limit=10)\n        assert src._load_state()[\"total_saved\"] == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `providers.py` — provider-specific overrides\n\n#### `MadagascarTribune._is_article_link` (providers.py:69)\nPure static method, untested, with several distinct exclusion rules.\n\n```python\nfrom providers import MadagascarTribune\n\nclass TestIsArticleLink:\n    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"href,expected\", [\n        (\"mon-article.html\", True),\n        (None, False),\n        (\"category-.html\", False),          # trailing \"-.html\" = category page\n        (\"http://external.com/x.html\", False),  # absolute/external\n        (\"/absolute/path.html\", False),\n        (\"_AuthorName,42_.html\", False),    # SPIP author page\n        (\"mon-article\", False),             # no .html suffix\n    ])\n    def test_classification(self, href, expected):\n        assert MadagascarTribune._is_article_link(href) is expected\n```\n\n#### `MadagascarTribune._discover_categories` and `list_article_urls` (providers.py:62,79)\nUntested. Pagination cutoff (`new_on_page == 0` breaks), the `_max_pages_per_category` safety cap, and redirect-following (`page_url = page.url`) are all unverified.\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\n\nclass TestMadagascarTribuneListArticleUrls:\n    @patch(\"providers.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_stops_when_page_has_no_new_links(self, mock_get):\n        home = MagicMock(html_content='<a href=\"spip.php?rubrique12\">x</a>')\n        empty_page = MagicMock(url=\"http://madagascar-tribune.com/rubrique12\", css=lambda s: [])\n        mock_get.side_effect = [home, empty_page]\n        src = MadagascarTribune()\n        assert list(src.list_article_urls()) == []\n\n    @patch(\"providers.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_respects_max_pages_per_category_cap(self, mock_get):\n        src = MadagascarTribune()\n        src._max_pages_per_category = 2\n        home = MagicMock(html_content='<a href=\"spip.php?rubrique1\">x</a>')\n        link_el = MagicMock()\n        link_el.attrib = {\"href\": \"some-article.html\"}\n        page = MagicMock(url=\"http://madagascar-tribune.com/rubrique1\", css=lambda s: [link_el] if s == \"a\" else [])\n        mock_get.side_effect = [home, page, page]  # always \"new\" content -> would loop forever without the cap\n        urls = list(src.list_article_urls())\n        assert mock_get.call_count == 1 + 2  # home + exactly max_pages_per_category\n```\n\n#### `FreeNews.list_article_urls` (providers.py:165)\nUntested. WP REST pagination, and the specific `HTTPError 400 == end of pages` vs. other HTTP errors distinction — a real error-handling gap: any other 4xx/5xx currently propagates and kills the whole crawl.\n\n```python\nimport urllib.error\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\nfrom providers import FreeNews\n\nclass TestFreeNewsListArticleUrls:\n    @patch(\"providers.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_paginates_until_empty_page(self, mock_urlopen):\n        page1 = MagicMock()\n        page1.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b'[{\"link\": \"http://a\"}]'\n        page2 = MagicMock()\n        page2.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b'[]'\n        mock_urlopen.side_effect = [page1, page2]\n        assert list(FreeNews().list_article_urls()) == [\"http://a\"]\n\n    @patch(\"providers.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_400_error_treated_as_end_of_pages(self, mock_urlopen):\n        page1 = MagicMock()\n        page1.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b'[{\"link\": \"http://a\"}]'\n        err = urllib.error.HTTPError(\"url\", 400, \"bad page\", {}, None)\n        mock_urlopen.side_effect = [page1, err]\n        assert list(FreeNews().list_article_urls()) == [\"http://a\"]\n\n    @patch(\"providers.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_non_400_http_error_propagates(self, mock_urlopen):\n        err = urllib.error.HTTPError(\"url\", 500, \"server error\", {}, None)\n        mock_urlopen.side_effect = [err]\n        with pytest.raises(urllib.error.HTTPError):\n            list(FreeNews().list_article_urls())\n\n    @patch(\"providers.urllib.request.urlopen\")\n    def test_post_missing_link_field_skipped(self, mock_urlopen):\n        page1 = MagicMock()\n        page1.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b'[{\"title\": \"no link\"}]'\n        page2 = MagicMock()\n        page2.__enter__.return_value.read.return_value = b'[]'\n        mock_urlopen.side_effect = [page1, page2]\n        assert list(FreeNews().list_article_urls()) == []\n```\n\n#### `Moov.list_article_urls` (providers.py:204)\nUntested — BFS frontier expansion, dedup via `queued`, filtering to `/article/` links only, and the swallowed-exception on frontier-expansion fetch failure (`except Exception: continue`, providers.py:225-226).\n\n```python\nclass TestMoovListArticleUrls:\n    @patch(\"providers.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_bfs_dedup_and_filters_non_article_links(self, mock_get):\n        link_article = MagicMock(); link_article.attrib = {\"href\": \"/article/1\"}\n        link_other = MagicMock(); link_other.attrib = {\"href\": \"/other/page\"}\n        home = MagicMock(css=lambda s: [link_article, link_other])\n        article_page = MagicMock(css=lambda s: [])  # no further links\n        mock_get.side_effect = [home, article_page]\n        urls = list(Moov().list_article_urls())\n        assert urls == [\"https://new.moov.mg/article/1\"]\n\n    @patch(\"providers.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_fetch_failure_during_expansion_does_not_crash(self, mock_get):\n        link = MagicMock(); link.attrib = {\"href\": \"/article/1\"}\n        home = MagicMock(css=lambda s: [link])\n        mock_get.side_effect = [home, ConnectionError(\"down\")]\n        urls = list(Moov().list_article_urls())\n        assert urls == [\"https://new.moov.mg/article/1\"]  # yielded before the failed expansion fetch\n\n    @patch(\"providers.Fetcher.get\")\n    def test_duplicate_article_link_not_requeued(self, mock_get):\n        link1 = MagicMock(); link1.attrib = {\"href\": \"/article/1\"}\n        link_dup = MagicMock(); link_dup.attrib = {\"href\": \"/article/1\"}\n        home = MagicMock(css=lambda s: [link1, link_dup])\n        mock_get.side_effect = [home]  # only one dequeue expected -> one more fetch call\n        urls = list(Moov().list_article_urls())\n        assert urls.count(\"https://new.moov.mg/article/1\") == 1\n```\n\n#### `PROVIDERS` registry (providers.py:271)\nUntested and cheap to cover — also would have caught the `radiomadagasikara-rnm` mismatch noted above.\n\n```python\nfrom providers import PROVIDERS\n\nclass TestProvidersRegistry:\n    def test_all_entries_are_newssource_subclasses(self):\n        from base import NewsSource\n        for cls in PROVIDERS.values():\n            assert issubclass(cls, NewsSource)\n\n    def test_key_matches_source_name(self):\n        for key, cls in PROVIDERS.items():\n            assert cls.source_name == key\n\n    def test_every_provider_can_list_or_has_sitemap(self):\n        # every provider either sets sitemap_url or overrides list_article_urls\n        for cls in PROVIDERS.values():\n            has_sitemap = cls.sitemap_url is not None\n            overrides = cls.list_article_urls is not __import__(\"base\").NewsSource.list_article_urls\n            assert has_sitemap or overrides, f\"{cls.source_name} has neither\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `main.py` — CLI, entirely untested\n\n```python\nimport sys\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\nfrom main import main\n\nclass TestMainCli:\n    @patch(\"main.PROVIDERS\", {\"fake\": MagicMock()})\n    def test_single_provider_invokes_crawl_once(self, monkeypatch, capsys):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"fake\", \"--limit\", \"5\"])\n        instance = main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"][\"fake\"].return_value\n        instance.crawl.return_value = []\n        instance._data_path = instance._state_path = instance._log_path = \"x\"\n        main()\n        instance.crawl.assert_called_once()\n        assert instance.crawl.call_args.kwargs[\"limit\"] == 5\n\n    @patch(\"main.PROVIDERS\", {\"a\": MagicMock(), \"b\": MagicMock()})\n    def test_all_invokes_every_provider(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"all\"])\n        for cls in main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"].values():\n            inst = cls.return_value\n            inst.crawl.return_value = []\n            inst._data_path = inst._state_path = inst._log_path = \"x\"\n        main()\n        for cls in main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"].values():\n            cls.return_value.crawl.assert_called_once()\n\n    def test_invalid_provider_name_exits(self, monkeypatch, capsys):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"not-a-real-provider\"])\n        with pytest.raises(SystemExit):\n            main()\n\n    def test_default_limit_is_ten(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"midi-madagasikara\"])\n        # inspect argparse defaults directly rather than running full crawl\n        import argparse\n        parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()\n        parser.add_argument(\"--limit\", type=int, default=10)\n        assert parser.parse_args([]).limit == 10\n```\n**Missing error-handling test:** `main()` has no try/except around `source.crawl(...)` — if `crawl()` re-raises (the discovery-failure path from `base.py:328-332`), `main()` with `provider=all` will abort the entire run after the first provider that hits a network error, rather than continuing to the next provider. Worth a test asserting current behavior (aborts) so a future fix (continue-on-error) is a deliberate change, not an accidental one.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `models.py`\nLow-value but cheap — mostly a sanity check that defaults behave (particularly `images: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)`, since a plain mutable default would be a classic bug).\n\n```python\nfrom models import Article, SiteSelectors\n\nclass TestModels:\n    def test_article_images_default_is_independent_list(self):\n        a1 = Article(url=\"u\", title=\"t\", body=\"b\", author=None, published_date=None,\n                      category=None, source=\"s\", scraped_at=\"now\")\n        a2 = Article(url=\"u2\", title=\"t\", body=\"b\", author=None, published_date=None,\n                      category=None, source=\"s\", scraped_at=\"now\")\n        a1.images.append(\"http://x\")\n        assert a2.images == []  # would fail if default_factory were a shared mutable default\n\n    def test_site_selectors_optional_defaults(self):\n        s = SiteSelectors(title=\"h1\", body=\"p\")\n        assert s.author is None\n        assert s.published_date_attr is None\n        assert s.published_date_format is None\n        assert s.category is None\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. Integration test gaps\n\nNone of the above exercises a full round-trip; each provider's real selectors have never been validated against representative HTML. Two levels worth adding beyond unit tests:\n\n1. **Selector-fixture integration tests** — for each provider, save a small representative HTML snapshot (fixture file under `tests/fixtures/<provider>.html`) and assert `parse_article` extracts the expected title/body/date/category from *real* markup, not the synthetic `FakePage`. This is the only way to catch the actual failure mode this crawler cares about most: a site changing its markup silently breaking a selector. Currently there is no signal for that at all.\n   ```python\n   @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"provider_cls,fixture\", [\n       (MidiMadagasikara, \"midi-madagasikara.html\"),\n       (LExpressMadagascar, \"lexpress-mg.html\"),\n       # ... one per provider\n   ])\n   def test_provider_selectors_match_real_fixture(provider_cls, fixture, monkeypatch):\n       html = (FIXTURES_DIR / fixture).read_text()\n       # requires wrapping scrapling's Fetcher/Adaptor around raw HTML instead of a live fetch\n       ...\n   ```\n\n2. **End-to-end `crawl()` against a stubbed provider** — one test that runs a fake `NewsSource` through `crawl()` twice in a row (simulating a resumed run) using a real tmp-path state/data dir, verifying: second run doesn't re-save first run's articles, `articles.jsonl` has correctly appended (not overwritten) entries, and `state.json` total_saved is cumulative. This is currently the single biggest blind spot — resumability is the entire design point of `crawl()` (per its docstring) and has no test proving it actually works across process boundaries.\n\n3. **`main.py` + `providers.py` wiring** — a smoke test that for every registered provider, `argparse` accepts its name as a valid `choices` value (would have caught the missing `radiomadagasikara-rnm` registration immediately).\n\n---\n\n### Priority if capacity is limited\n1. `crawl()` orchestration tests (§2) — highest risk, most complex control flow, directly governs data integrity across runs.\n2. `parse_article` / `_extract_images` (§2) — the actual value-producing logic; currently zero coverage means any refactor is unverifiable.\n3. `parse_french_date` / `parse_numeric_date` (§1) — small, pure, cheap to fully cover, and the numeric-date `ValueError` gap is a real bug candidate.\n4. Provider-specific `list_article_urls` overrides (§3) — three different crawling strategies (SPIP pagination, WP REST API, BFS spider), each with untested termination/error conditions.\n5. `main.py` (§4) and `models.py` (§5) — cheap, do last.\n",
