        "title": "4. `main.py` — CLI, entirely untested",
        "content": "\n```python\nimport sys\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\nfrom main import main\n\nclass TestMainCli:\n    @patch(\"main.PROVIDERS\", {\"fake\": MagicMock()})\n    def test_single_provider_invokes_crawl_once(self, monkeypatch, capsys):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"fake\", \"--limit\", \"5\"])\n        instance = main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"][\"fake\"].return_value\n        instance.crawl.return_value = []\n        instance._data_path = instance._state_path = instance._log_path = \"x\"\n        main()\n        instance.crawl.assert_called_once()\n        assert instance.crawl.call_args.kwargs[\"limit\"] == 5\n\n    @patch(\"main.PROVIDERS\", {\"a\": MagicMock(), \"b\": MagicMock()})\n    def test_all_invokes_every_provider(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"all\"])\n        for cls in main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"].values():\n            inst = cls.return_value\n            inst.crawl.return_value = []\n            inst._data_path = inst._state_path = inst._log_path = \"x\"\n        main()\n        for cls in main.__globals__[\"PROVIDERS\"].values():\n            cls.return_value.crawl.assert_called_once()\n\n    def test_invalid_provider_name_exits(self, monkeypatch, capsys):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"not-a-real-provider\"])\n        with pytest.raises(SystemExit):\n            main()\n\n    def test_default_limit_is_ten(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [\"main.py\", \"midi-madagasikara\"])\n        # inspect argparse defaults directly rather than running full crawl\n        import argparse\n        parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()\n        parser.add_argument(\"--limit\", type=int, default=10)\n        assert parser.parse_args([]).limit == 10\n```\n**Missing error-handling test:** `main()` has no try/except around `source.crawl(...)` — if `crawl()` re-raises (the discovery-failure path from `base.py:328-332`), `main()` with `provider=all` will abort the entire run after the first provider that hits a network error, rather than continuing to the next provider. Worth a test asserting current behavior (aborts) so a future fix (continue-on-error) is a deliberate change, not an accidental one.\n\n---\n\n",
