      {
        "title": "6. Integration test gaps",
        "content": "\nNone of the above exercises a full round-trip; each provider's real selectors have never been validated against representative HTML. Two levels worth adding beyond unit tests:\n\n1. **Selector-fixture integration tests** — for each provider, save a small representative HTML snapshot (fixture file under `tests/fixtures/<provider>.html`) and assert `parse_article` extracts the expected title/body/date/category from *real* markup, not the synthetic `FakePage`. This is the only way to catch the actual failure mode this crawler cares about most: a site changing its markup silently breaking a selector. Currently there is no signal for that at all.\n   ```python\n   @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"provider_cls,fixture\", [\n       (MidiMadagasikara, \"midi-madagasikara.html\"),\n       (LExpressMadagascar, \"lexpress-mg.html\"),\n       # ... one per provider\n   ])\n   def test_provider_selectors_match_real_fixture(provider_cls, fixture, monkeypatch):\n       html = (FIXTURES_DIR / fixture).read_text()\n       # requires wrapping scrapling's Fetcher/Adaptor around raw HTML instead of a live fetch\n       ...\n   ```\n\n2. **End-to-end `crawl()` against a stubbed provider** — one test that runs a fake `NewsSource` through `crawl()` twice in a row (simulating a resumed run) using a real tmp-path state/data dir, verifying: second run doesn't re-save first run's articles, `articles.jsonl` has correctly appended (not overwritten) entries, and `state.json` total_saved is cumulative. This is currently the single biggest blind spot — resumability is the entire design point of `crawl()` (per its docstring) and has no test proving it actually works across process boundaries.\n\n3. **`main.py` + `providers.py` wiring** — a smoke test that for every registered provider, `argparse` accepts its name as a valid `choices` value (would have caught the missing `radiomadagasikara-rnm` registration immediately).\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
